Now,
 $S=\displaystyle\frac{1}{3}+\frac{2}{3^2}+\frac{3}{3^3}+\cdots+\frac{k}{3^k}+\cdots$
Now
\begin{align*}
&\begin{array}{rcl}
3S&=&1+\displaystyle\frac{2}{3}+\frac{3}{3^2}+\frac{4}{3^3}\cdots+\frac{k}{3^{k-1}}+\cdots\\
S&=&\phantom{1} \ \displaystyle\frac{1}{3}+\frac{2}{3^2}+\frac{3}{3^3}+\cdots+\frac{(k-1)}{3^{k-1}}+\cdots
\end{array}\\
\therefore\quad
&\begin{array}{rcl}
2S&=&1+\displaystyle\frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{3^2}+\frac{1}{3^3}+\cdots+\frac{1}{3^{k-1}}+\cdots\\
&=& \dfrac{1}{1-\frac{1}{3}}= \dfrac{3}{2}
\end{array}\\
\therefore \ S&=&\dfrac{3}{4}
\end{align*}<answer>$\dfrac{3}{4}$</answer>

